<TITLE> Nine parties collect forms so far: EC </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 28 (bdnews24.com)  Nine political parties have collected forms to register with the Election Commission, an election official said Thursday. EC secretariat deputy secretary (administration) Jesmine Tuli told bdnews24.com the parties collected registration forms and copies of rules from the EC secretariat on Thursday. The parties are Jatiya Samajtantrik Dal (JSD), Bangladesh Sacheton Nagorik Mancha, Jamiat-e-Ulema Islami Bangladesh, Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), Bangladesh Muslim Krishak Sramik Oikya Jote, National People's Party (NPP), Islamic Constitution Movement (ICM), Bangladesh Khelafat Majlish and Nirdoliyo Jano Andolon. According to the registration rules, documents on 10 matters in a specified form (Form-1) attested by the general secretary of the party must be attached with the application for registration. The information to be provided are: party name and address of the head office, party constitution, election manifesto (if any), rules of the party (if any), party logo and picture of the party flag, names and designations of all members of the party central or equivalent committee, name of the bank account operated in the name of the party, accounts number and latest balance, description of the source of party funds, power of attorney given in favour of the applicant for the registration and copy of the treasury clearance of the registration fees. Besides, documents in support of the party's fulfillment of registration conditions, under the rules of new amended electoral laws, would have to be submitted. The Election Commission will scrutinise whether the conditions for registration have been fulfilled and the attached documents are genuine, and publish notice in the national dailies in this regard. If any fault were detected, the party would be given 15 days to rectify it. After completing all formalities, the EC will issue a registration certificate to the party, but according to law, the EC if required can cancel the registration. The Election Commission has announced a schedule from Aug 27 to Oct 15 for political parties to apply for registration, the chief election commissioner said Monday. The commission wants to finalise the registration procedure by Oct 30, CEC ATM Shamsul Huda said. "The commission has sent the draft of the registration regulations for political partiesin line with new electoral lawsto the law ministry," he told reporters at the EC Secretariat. The caretaker government on Aug 19 published the new Representation of the People Order (Amendment) Ordinance 2008, making registration of all political parties mandatory. bdnews24
